stress well, good at assessing weather, excellent computer skills. Weaknesses: weak memory for numbers, makes nasty remarks about colleagues. Calmness: handles stress well => good. Teamwork: nasty remarks negative. Reliability: conscientious good. Technical: good.\n\nC: strengths: makes correct decisions quickly, keeps calm in crisis, understands complicated technology. Weaknesses: difficulty communicating ideas, egocentric, not willing to further education. Calmness good. Decision-making good. Teamwork poor.\n\nD: strengths: responds adequately to unexpected events, concentrates well, solves problems extremely well, takes responsibility seriously. Weaknesses: regarded as arrogant, hot temper, know-it-all, weak leadership. Calmness: adequate but not explicit. Teamwork: poor due to arrogance, hot temper.\n\nWhich candidate best fits long-distance pilot? Need reliability, calmness, decision-making, teamwork, professional development. B seems reliable, handles stress, but interpersonal negative remarks. C is calm, good decisions, technical, but poor communication and not willing to develop. A has strong leadership but unfriendly and not open to new ideas. D has good problem solving but arrogance and hot temper.\n\nProbably candidate B or C? B's nasty remarks could be serious for crew. C's egocentric and communication difficulty also problematic. Between them, B's stress handling and conscientiousness may outweigh communication issues? But nasty remarks could degrade crew morale. C's calmness and quick correct decisions are valuable, but communication difficulty and egocentric may be worse. Also not willing to further education is a long-term issue.\n\nA's leadership could offset unfriendly? But not open to new ideas is a problem for long-distance evolving tech. D's hot temper is concerning.\n\nThus maybe B is best overall: conscientious, handles stress, good technical, though memory weakness and nasty remarks. Memory for numbers could be mitigated with checklists. Nast